#compdef pushpin-handler
# ============================================================================
# pushpin-handler - Pushpin reverse proxy handler component
#                    (Rust + C++, Apache-2.0)
#
# Author : Fastly (formerly Fanout)
# Upstream: https://github.com/fastly/pushpin
# crate  : pushpin (workspace)
#
# `pushpin-handler` is the long-lived connection handler
# component of Pushpin - Fastly's open-source reverse
# proxy that adds HTTP push (long-poll, SSE, WebSocket)
# to any HTTP backend without the backend itself having
# to be push-aware. Pushpin sits in front of a request /
# response backend and the *handler* component holds
# subscribed client connections + delivers messages
# published to them via the Pushpin EPCP protocol. Pushpin
# powers Fastly's Fanout product (the in-CDN push fabric)
# and is also self-hostable as a single multi-binary
# install.
#
# The Pushpin install ships ~7 binaries:
#   pushpin           - top-level launcher (config-driven)
#   pushpin-proxy     - request/response proxying
#   pushpin-handler   - this binary; long-lived
#                       connection management + JWT-auth +
#                       EPCP message dispatch
#   pushpin-connmgr   - dedicated connection manager
#                       (low-level socket handling)
#   pushpin-publish   - CLI publisher (push from terminal)
#   pushpin-legacy    - legacy single-process daemon
#   m2adapter         - Mongrel2 protocol bridge
#
# Usage:
#   pushpin-handler [OPTIONS]
#
# Flags (clap derive Parser):
#   -c, --config <file>     - path to configuration file
#                              (default: standard pushpin
#                               install location)
#   -l, --logfile <file>    - path to log file (default
#                              stderr)
#   -L, --loglevel <0..4>   - 0=error, 1=warn, 2=info,
#                              3=debug, 4=trace (default 2)
#       --verbose           - same as --loglevel=3
#       --ipc-prefix <p>    - prefix added to all ZeroMQ
#                              IPC filenames; lets multiple
#                              pushpin instances coexist
#                              on one host
#       --port-offset <n>   - increment all ZeroMQ TCP
#                              ports + the HTTP control
#                              server port by n
#   -h, --help              - print help
#   -V, --version           - print version
#
# The jsonwebtoken (JWT) lane is built on `jsonwebtoken =
# "9"` (declared at upstream Cargo.toml HEAD as a direct
# dep, used from src/core/jwt.rs), the canonical Rust JWT
# library by Vincent Prouillet (Keats) - github.com/Keats/
# jsonwebtoken, 1700+ stars. The crate implements RFC 7519
# (JSON Web Token), RFC 7515 (JSON Web Signature), and
# RFC 7518 (JSON Web Algorithms) - sign / verify JWTs with
# HMAC (HS256/HS384/HS512), RSA (RS256/PS256/...), ECDSA
# (ES256/ES384), and EdDSA (EdDSA / Ed25519). The library
# defaults to `ring` for cryptographic primitives with an
# optional `rust_crypto` feature flag for the pure-Rust
# backend.
#
# pushpin-handler uses JWT for the publisher-auth path:
# the EPCP control channel accepts inbound publish
# requests, and each request is authenticated via a JWT
# bearer token. The token is verified with the configured
# secret (HS256 by default) before the message is
# dispatched to subscribed client connections. The
# `src/core/jwt.rs` module wraps `jsonwebtoken::decode`
# with pushpin-specific claim validation (iss / aud / exp).
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 241 :: JSON Web Tokens (RFC 7519 sign + verify)
# Round 1421 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 241
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis
# (proposed):
#   Rust    : Keats/jsonwebtoken           - RFC 7519 +
#                                            RFC 7515 +
#                                            RFC 7518 impl
#                                            with ring or
#                                            RustCrypto
#                                            backend
#   Go      : golang-jwt/jwt               - the fork of
#                                            dgrijalva/jwt
#                                            after the
#                                            2021 community
#                                            takeover;
#                                            still uses the
#                                            github.com/
#                                            golang-jwt/jwt
#                                            import path
#   TS/Node : auth0/node-jsonwebtoken      - the Auth0-
#                                            maintained
#                                            Node JWT lib
#                                            (jsonwebtoken
#                                            on npm) with
#                                            sync + async
#                                            sign / verify
#                                            and full RFC
#                                            7519 + 7515 +
#                                            7518 coverage
#
# JWT is a clean spec-bound axis - RFC 7519 defines the
# JSON Web Token vocabulary (header + payload + signature
# Base64URL-joined with `.`), RFC 7515 the JSON Web
# Signature container, and RFC 7518 the JSON Web Algorithm
# registry. Compliant libraries produce + verify byte-
# identical tokens for the same key + payload + algorithm
# combination. The three lanes converge at the wire
# format level (a JWT minted by golang-jwt/jwt verifies
# identically against Keats/jsonwebtoken and
# auth0/node-jsonwebtoken).
#
# Structural commentary:
#   - Keats/jsonwebtoken (Rust): the Rust ecosystem JWT
#     library; depends on `ring` by default for crypto
#     primitives (with a `rust_crypto` opt-in feature for
#     a pure-Rust crypto backend)
#   - golang-jwt/jwt (Go): the community-maintained fork
#     of dgrijalva/jwt - the original author abandoned
#     the library in 2020, and a community group forked
#     it under github.com/golang-jwt/jwt (the import path
#     is intentionally unchanged for drop-in upgrade)
#   - auth0/node-jsonwebtoken (Node): Auth0's npm package
#     `jsonwebtoken` - the de-facto Node JWT library,
#     maintained by Auth0 since the original sequester of
#     the namespace in 2014
#
# Three different maintainership stories, three different
# crypto-primitive choices, converging on RFC 7519 wire
# format. Axis 241 opens with the Rust slot at the canonical
# Rust JWT library family.
# ============================================================================

_pushpin-handler() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(-c --config)'{-c,--config}'[path to configuration file]:file:_files' \
        '(-l --logfile)'{-l,--logfile}'[path to log file]:file:_files' \
        '(-L --loglevel)'{-L,--loglevel}'[log level (1-4)]:level:(1 2 3 4)' \
        '--verbose[same as --loglevel=3]' \
        '--ipc-prefix[prefix added to ZeroMQ IPC filenames]:prefix:' \
        '--port-offset[increment ZeroMQ TCP ports + HTTP control port by n]:offset:' \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]'
}

_pushpin-handler "$@"
